The Very Best of Prince is a compilation of a widely acclaimed pop/dance-pop artist whose recordings are known for strong studio production, clear arrangements, and a mix of uptempo, danceable tracks and polished ballads. Those characteristics play well to someone who enjoys listening to CDs for their sonic quality and variety: a Prince compilation typically delivers a compact, high-recognition playlist of distinct, well-produced singles that show off dynamics, vocal detail, and rhythmic clarity that a CD format reproduces faithfully. Because it spans multiple styles within pop and dance-pop, it offers immediate engagement and replay value for a general listener without requiring prior familiarity with a particular band's album flow.
The alternative, a "Greatest Hits" in Classic Rock/AOR, can also be excellent, but AOR and album-oriented classic rock often emphasize longer, album-context tracks and guitar-driven arrangements that may be more appealing to listeners already invested in that specific band or subgenre. In contrast, a curated "Very Best of Prince" compilation is more likely to provide broad appeal and instant, varied listening pleasure for someone whose only stated preference is enjoying CDs themselves. For those reasons I chose The Very Best of Prince and rejected the Classic Rock/AOR Greatest Hits as the less universally engaging option for a general CD enthusiast.

