- I reject the Fleetwood Mac option because its defining features are the ones I explicitly dislike: low‑compression, dynamics‑preserving mastering and lush multitracked harmonies that create a spacious, vocal‑forward, album‑focused experience. While those qualities are excellent for listeners who prize vintage texture and narrative cohesion, they work against my preference for compressed, punchy, front‑of‑stage masters that prioritize immediate momentum and riff/groove impact. The Fleetwood Mac description emphasizes restored headroom and restrained arrangements that would, in my view, sap the raw punch and visceral forwardness I want.
