Candidate 2 (Fleetwood Mac) has attractive elements—warm analog tape sheen, tactile midrange and palpable solos—but it also embodies several of my explicit dislikes. Its preserved microdynamics, natural lead vocals within lush, multitracked harmonies and "album‑centric sequencing" point to a low‑compression, ensemble‑depth presentation that can sap the immediate momentum and front‑of‑stage punch I prefer. The emphasis on ensemble depth and album narrative runs counter to my desire for punchy, singles‑forward sequencing and slightly compressed mastering that drives riffs and propulsive low end. In short, Fleetwood Mac offers a more laid‑back, narrative and harmony‑forward experience that conflicts with my priority for upfront aggression, compressed punch and riff‑forward immediacy.
