Evaluation against the two candidates:
1) The piano‑centered early‑70s double LP explicitly offers warm tape sheen, preserved headroom and low‑compression mastering, urgent piano transients, tactile breathy midrange lead vocals, lush multitracked harmonies, wide stereo imaging, palpable solos and album sequencing that rewards start‑to‑finish listening. Those attributes directly match my stated preferences: tape coloration, low compression, preserved transient detail and microdynamics, breathy midrange vocals with ambience, wide staging, and strong album flow. It also avoids the dislikes by emphasizing preserved headroom (not brick‑walled), tape sheen rather than glossy remaster treatment, and wide imaging rather than narrow or dead‑centered vocals.
